\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Nothing whatever. No, never, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What about help from other relatives? You mentioned these uncles, did she get financial aid from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, she never got anything from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Would they have been in a position to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, yes, there was one in London was a \'85 in a printing 
office, I think he was a reader, or something and he was doing very, very well, but, you know, he didn't take any interest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 So she wouldn't have ever asked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, good heavens, no!
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And he never offered anything, you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Could we get on to when you left school. Can you tell me about that, leaving school and starting your first job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes. Well, as I said, you know, we could leave at 13 in those days, and actually, from the point of view of what I could learn at
 that school, I'd gone through all the classes and even at that age the last 9 months \'85
 myself, along with one or two more were doing all sorts of odd jobs and, you know tabulating the library and all those sort of jobs because we had been through the normal sort of classes and there was nothing more for us, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What standard did you pass then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
It was standard 7. So from that point of view I wasn't losing anything there, but I did lose the opportunity of going to a grammar school, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What kind of school was it, was it a council school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It was a council school, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Was it the same one as your friend went to, Mr. Spurgeon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I think he did, only, you see, I'm older than him, and therefore \'85 I think Reg was there at a very bad time, really, when \'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 He was there in the War
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 That's so, yes, and from what he's told me, you know, they had a poor set of masters with no respect for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 He did say they had this very good headmaster and I wondered if you had the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, Mr. Morton Matthews, oh, yes. I've got one of his etchings out there. Wonderful man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 He was your headmaster, too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 He was my headmaster, yes, and we also had an assistant master who was an excellent fellow. I owe a lot
 to him; Edward Baker, he was a Quaker and \'85
 well, he influenced my life a lot. And afterwards, when I came back after the First World War one or two of them had just started what they called an adult school in Halstead. Apparently that was a National move
ment, but mostly in the Midlands, you didn't get much of it round here \'85 which was for educating \'85 you know, further education of adults, coupled with the \'85
 well, it really was a religious movement, as well, but broad in its basis and willing to study everything else, \'85 and he was president, this assistant master, that had been my master, and he got me to go along. I joined up and \'85
 Let me see, that was incidental.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It's just a bit outside the programme. It is very interesting to get some idea of the ki
nd of influences on a person because that influence obviously started while you were at school, did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes. Oh, yes. He was very sorry that, you know, circumstances were not \'85
 you know, that I could have gone. But I had the greatest respect for that man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember him actually teaching you himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What subjects did he teach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, the used to take the general, you see, they took the class, then, and they took us through the whole curriculum.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What did you particularly enjoy in the way of school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well, I was very fond of history. Yes, that used to fascinate me, what little that, you know, he was able to you. And he was, in that sense, I think he was a good teacher, like, but he could present
 it to you and he was an excellent reader and that whetted my appetite for it, you know, only just a smattering.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 In what kind of way would he present it? The history?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, it wasn't just, sort of, you know, read out as facts from a book. I mea
n he would talk even then, although he wasn't a Socialist, he was a liberal minded man, and he would about, you know, the social sort of aspect of history, which we didn't learn much about, you know. I mean for instance, like, such a thing as the story of
 Watt Tyler, you know. Well, I mean, it wasn't just dismissed and going on to the kings, I mean he would talk about that with some \'85 I can see now, with some understanding. He was a man like that, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did your parents ever meet him? I mean, did the parents ever meet the teachers at all at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
No. Unless someone brought a boy down who they thought had been called severely and they'd bring them down. You know, have an argy-bargy, but ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You don't remember your mother ever going up to the school, or your father, for anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
And do you think this particular teacher and headmaster, did they know many working people? I mean, did they have personal experience of their lives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, well, he did, because his
 father, although I suppose you would call him lower middle class, his father was a tailor. I don't mean a master tailor, I mean he was working as a tailor. You know, he knew working people, and he was a good athlete and his sport was all with the working
 men of the town. Yes, I think he had a good knowledge of \'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Of conditions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, of conditions, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember any musical activity in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, as a matter of fact this particular teacher used to bring his clarinet and
 he used to play his clarinet. And the headmaster that Reg spoke about, Mr. Morton Matthews, he was quite a good musician, you know he was a very good piano player. As a matter of fact he was a very, very, artistic cultured man. Very. I mean, in every asp
ect of the arts, like, he had quite a good knowledge, and \'85 To be in, you know, in an ordinary elementary school you just wonder how such a man could have remained there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, I suppose he enjoyed teaching?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, and he was such a pleasing personality. He was a wonderful man and he really had \'85
 he was held in high regard by generations of students. He retired, then he came back to us, to this adult school, to speak to us one Sunday. He was blind, he couldn't see anything at all, but just as cheerful and pleasant to listen to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 As before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes. A wonderful man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 When you left school you started work. Could you tell me something about it? The hours and conditions, and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes. Well, when I started work \'85 Along the road where I lived there was a workshop of a painter. I mean a house painter, not a \'85
 and I got a job with him at half a crown a week, and that was from 6 o'clock in the morning until 6 o'clock in the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What did the work consist of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, it consi
sted of generally making meself useful, doing all those odd jobs, those dirty jobs that they didn't want to keep a tradesman on, such as scraping the old paint off fences, and cleaning out \'85
 you know, troughing that goes round house, you know, preparatory to painting, and rubbing down, and \'85
 you know, that sort of thing. And then doing sort of the rough work, like painting the troughing and all those sort of things that have to be done, and you don't want a tradesman to do it. And things inside \'85 well, you'
d be scraping the paint off walls and washing ceilings and \'85 all those sort of things, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How did you feel about the work? What was your attitude to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, I \'85 it didn't hold any interest for me, but you see \'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did you think that at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, looking back, you see \'85 I never wore a chip on my shoulder. I happen to be \'85
 I suppose, being blessed with good health, and well fed, you know, my disposition was such that, you know, I never wore a chip on my shoulder, or I could even, in circumstances like that \'85 I don't know \'85
 and being with other people and that sort of thing I'd still get something out of life. I never, as I say, remember going round feeling sore.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And the man you worked with, the painter, how did you get along with him? Well, do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Oh, yes. Well, actually there were several of them, because, you see, a master painter in those days, they didn't regularly employ men sort of for 12 months of the year, you see, they used to contract them, maybe doin
g a large house up, you see. Then if they got the contract then they had certain people who they used to offer a job, because there was usually someone out of work, you see, and they used to sort of take them on, like, for that job, so there were always p
eople coming and going. And sometimes you'd be working so that you'd move into a large house, perhaps there'd be a dozen of you, you see, and so from that point of view, from a sort of \'85
 you know, relationship with other people there was always something interesting because, you know, some of them were local characters and all that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What would be their age on the whole? Were they a lot older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You were the only boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I was the only boy, yes, I mean that would \'85 they would be - what? - anything up to 65, and, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Now, you were saying that they were older than you, but they were nice to you, were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Generally speaking they were, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You didn't feel lonely being the only boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, I don't remember \'85 you know, having sort of any upset or trouble with any of them. Maybe I was lucky, but \'85
 or they were, perhaps, a better type of chap than usual, but never had any trouble with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What time in the morning did you have to start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, 6 o'clock in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It was nearly all 6 for everything, wasn't it, round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It was, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What time did you stop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Six o'clock. Mind you, if we were, like, at one of these houses in the country, well th
en, you see, we used to travel in their time, you see, which meant that if you had to cycle or walk, well, you used to knock off at, say half past 5, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What were your breaks in the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, there was a breakfast break, half an hour, and there was an hour, or three-quarters of an hour for lunch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did you bring your own food for those breaks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What did you take with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Sometimes a piece of bacon and, you know, fry it on a stick. Used to rather
 like that. Shall I say something out of the ordinary, you know. And I used to take, you know, sometimes and egg, you know, spread on \'85 you know, boiled hard and spread on sort of bread and butter. Sometimes, you know, potted meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And cheese ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Sometimes cheese, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 But not regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Anything to drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Tea, yes. But then you used to brew up yourself, you see, where you were on the job, sort of thing, you know, you didn't used to have to take \'85 not convey it, like, individually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How long did you keep that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Only just over a year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How did you get the job, by the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, it happened to be that the master painted was an uncle of one of the boys that I was friendly with, you see, and sort of p
laying around with this lad, and his aunt got to know that, you know, I was leaving school and she spoke to her husband and, you know, said what about giving me a job. That's really how it came about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And when you left that job after about a year you would have been 15, would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, just over 14.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And when you were just over 14, what was the next job you did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well the next job I did was as a boy down at Courtaulds' factory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Can you tell me about that? What was the pay, to begin with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well, I got a shilling increase. I got 3/6d. a week there. And then after a little while I used to go in 10 minutes early, or a quarter of an hour early in the morning, you know, between half past 5 and quarter to 6 and light up the gas ligh
ts, because they had some electricity, but nearly all gaslight then, you see, and there little lights, They used to go round with the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13648689\charrsid6246232 gas lighter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232  and sort of light them, and I got another 6d, a week for that, you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How long did you continue getting that extra sixpence a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Not very long, about a year, because then I got moved on to another job and I got, you know, a little more money and I moved away from that. But the first job was actually oiling some very fast running spindles. You see,
 there was one process there in what's called the throwing of the silk where they put the turns in to strengthen it \'85
 you know what I mean, don't you? Well, they put that in at high speed, you see. These bobbins are upended and they was all like this, you see, and going at that speed it puts the turns in the thread, you see, which in its \'85
 which strengthens it. And, you see, to make a perfect thread, to throw it properly, the spindles had got to move freely. You see, if they were running hot or anything was
 obstructing them, then, of course, that made an uneven twist, you see, so they had to be oiled frequently. And my job was to go round with a little tray full of oil, with just a little hole in the top and \'85 well, like a little thin spoon, a piece of 
\'85 you
 know, flat wire, really, it was, and I used to put it in the tray and then just put a drop of oil on the bearing of the spindle, you see. And of course, there were thousands of those to do, you see. Used to go along like that ((hand demonstration)). Got 
quite expert, you know, that sort of business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And you did that all day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I did that all day. Nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did you find it had any physical effect on you, doing that repetitious work all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, but frightfully boring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You were conscious of it being boring at the time, even though as you said, you weren't a discontented person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes. Oh, yes. You'd be just \'85
 you'd stop and look along and you'd see thousands of those things, you know, all along that row where you've to go and then when you've done that row you'd start and come back on another row just the same and that was \'85 you know that went on all day.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You don't remember it having any effect on your vision?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I don't mean any permanent effect on your vision, I just wondered if you could read a page of print after a day's work like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 After you'd finished work how did you feel? Did you feel very tired?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I can't recall that. No, I can't recall. You see, that wasn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13648689\charrsid6246232 laborious}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 , it was just binding and, you know, soul-destroying, but then at 14 you don't think in terms of soul-destroying jobs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You mean you think it's more in retrospect you think of it like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Now? Oh, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What were your relationships like with the people there? Did you have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, they were queer. I mean, it was a \'85
 in a sense, sort of one of amusement, because to me it was like being in another world. You see, this particular department was where they put the old people, 
sort of thing, you know, when they were beyond certain other jobs they used to put them there, not doing what I was doing but in that department. You see, the putting of these bobbins on the stands and that sort of thing, which was very simple and didn't 
require any skill, you see, that used to be given to these \'85 to me they seemed like, you know \'85 well, they were very old people 'cos, I mean, I was 14 and they were people, probably of my age now, but, you see, they were \'85
 they looked so old, you know, and 
they were old, I mean, people wore their age then. And then, you see, many of them had had a lifetime's hard graft, they'd reared families, the women and they'd been at work, as well, while they were rearing families. The men were old and they'd had a rou
gh time generally, and \'85 And, you know, I used to look at them and thing, you know \'85 it's like being in another world, you see. There was one or two of us boys, only about one or two, and the rest were these very \'85 well, they seemed to me \'85
 these very old people, you know, bent and grey, and men breaded, you know, grey-bearded. And the old ladies, little old ladies, they seemed to be, with shawls slung over their shoulder, you know, and long frocks trailing. I've a very clear picture of 
\'85.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And you think, really, they were probably what sort of age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, they'd be round about my \'85
 they wouldn't be as old as me, or about my age. I mean it's difficult for me to realize that, but it was so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 People seemed old at forty in those days, I think. You look at photographs and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did they talk to you? Did you have any companionship from them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, yes. The old ladies, like, I mean, in the main, you know, they like young boys and they used to talk to you friendly. 
Some were nasty, crabbed, as old people do get, and, you know, some of the old men were nasty-tempered. It was a queer set-up really, I mean, fantastic for a young lad to be dropped in with such company, but \'85
 But still, you know, it didn't worry me unduly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You didn't find it depressing on your spirits to be with such old people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, it never depressed me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you think they were rather a quiet lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 They were quiet. Oh, yes, I think they'd had all the life knocked out of them, you know, one way and another. Yes, they were a quiet lot.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You didn't have a sort of joking kind of time at work like some boys have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, no, there was no \'85 I don't think there was any joke left in that crowd. There was a little bit of, you know, silly 
little back-biting and all the silly little things that people do when they get into their second childhood - watching another one, you know, thinking that another one has got a little more advantage than the other one. Most extraordinary how they can get
 like that, you know. But that's really pathetic because, I mean, they \'85 it wasn't pathetic to me then because, I mean, I \'85 the world \'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You didn't understand so much when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How long did you stay with that particular crowd?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, not very long, no. Six months, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And then where did you move to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
I went into a yarn store, it was where they did store the yarn in bobbins and used to separate it and issue it, but identification marks on some of the bobbins so that \'85
 because yarn looked very much a like although it could be very different, and we used to put identification marks on the bobbins so that, you know, they didn't get mixed. There, they were nearly all young people there. About a couple o
f old men who were soured, and that sort of thing, but in the main they were young people. And of course, being high spirited, like, you know, we used to sort of have quite a happy time, like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You were allowed to talk freely, were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Was there quite a relaxed atmosphere in the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It wasn't too bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Were you overseen a lot, did you have \'85?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, not a lot. Much depended on the overseer, or foreman, but in the main at this \'85 you know, pretty decent like. 
As far as the young lads were concerned there usually used to be 3 or 4 sacked every week, you know. They used to get up to their antics and there was always plenty of lads about who were wanting to go down there because it was always thought, well, if yo
u got a job at the factory, like, you know, you was all right, like, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You mean it was security? You could have a future.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 That's right, yes, but in the process, like, as I say, you know, there were \'85 it was such a large building and, you
 see, if one wanted to play tricks and, you know, get away from your job, and that, you could do there, and I mean, you could do it probably for some time. But what used to be, like, they used to get so bad that, you know, eventually the exasperated forem
an would, you know, get hold of them and take them into the manager and without much thought he just used to sack them, you see. That was how it was. I mean, it wasn't always anything to do with whether they were good or bad boys, it was just that \'85
 well, they'd been caught, you know, where they shouldn't be, or something like that, and they'd be just \'85 you know, sack them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 They wouldn't get a warning, or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Sometimes they would. Yes, sometimes they would, but he happened to be a man \'85
 and I can understand it, I mean, with a lot of boys, and that sort of thing, and some of them were, you know \'85. a job, I mean, the best solution, like, was to get rid of you. It didn't mean anything to him, he'd get another one just the same. And tha
t was, you know, how it appertained there. But in the main, you know, conditions weren't too bad, and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And if you were late at work? I remember you describing to me about an old lady once, could you tell me again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, you
 see, they had a rule there that at 6 o'clock the main gates were closed and if you were not in then there was no letting you through another door or anything like that. You were out, and you had to lose what was called 'a quarter', assuming they meant a 
q
uarter of the day, you see, and you could not return to work then until after the breakfast break, you see, which was quarter past 8 when they used to stop work. Well, you see, obviously there were occasions when people would be late, because, I mean, the
y
 had to walk in, they had families, there were all those things which could legitimately cause people to be late. It didn't make any difference. The old gatekeeper had had his instructions to shut the gate at 6, and shut the gate at 6 he would. And it was
 in my very early days I do remember one old lady who somehow or other had got half in and half out and he was pushing this gate from the inside, you see to shut the gate - and incidentally, he'd got her in between the two gates and \'85
 by the waist here, somewhere - and she was battering on his chest, like this and \'85 you know, her legs were outside there \'85
 and you know, that really did shock me. I did think what a brute he was, you know. But he was an old soldier and one of those people, like, who you do find
, especially among old soldiers, you know, very easy on the tongue, and, you know, if any Courtaulds came around there, you know, 'Yes, Sir', 'No, Sir', and all that business that goes with it, which plenty of old soldiers were pretty good at, you know. R
ascals, really, but, you know \'85
 When I say 'rascals' I mean not totally beyond the pale, but up to al the tricks. And he was one of them sort and consequently, you know, they all thought, you know, 'oh, John Howard, a good chap'. And he could do that sort of thing and get away with it.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Were you ever late?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Yes, I've been late once or twice, you know. I think everyone was at some time or other. Then latterly that eased off and you used to be allowed to go and sit in the lodge while they sent up to 
your foreman and ask your foreman whether you could come in, you see. And that gradually eased, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 But not while you were there this time, that we are talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, no, not then. Not then. I mean, it was possible for women to walk in
 3 or 4 miles from Greenstead Green or from Gosfield, or Maplestead and still have to wait about until, you know, 9 o'clock before they could start work which, apart from the loss of money, you see, there was nowhere for them to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 At that time, up to 1918, were there any clubs, or any kind of benefits, or sporting facilities connected with the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, oh, yes. In fact, there was quite a lot, and for an industrial concern they \'85
 that company had a record probably as good as, you know, many, like \'85
 For instance, these girls that came in from you know, the villages and from Haverhill, and that sort of thing, who had to lodge in the town, for them they did commence a night school. They built a school where they could be taught needlework and 
lots of other domestic things, and they did employ a welfare sort of worker, sort of a welfare worker-cum-nurse sort of person who, you know, used to get interested in the girls and \'85
 they did quite a lot of that. And also if anyone was ill they would have a visitor \'85
 you know, a sick - visitor would go and sort of visit them, and she had the authority to see that they got, for instance, a pint of milk a day and little things like that, you know. It doesn't seem much now, but then, of course, it was rather \'85
. I well remember my father, you know, having this milk. And again, that was typical of Mother, like, you know, she wouldn't ask for it and he was ill for a long, long time before one of his fellow workmates sort of said, 'you ought to be having that milk
', sort of thing. And so he sort of raised the matter and that came along, but ... and mind you, it was very, very acceptable, a pint of milk in those days. Things like that, you know, they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember this visitor coming to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, I knew her very well. She was the wife of a \'85
 a sort of queer mixture of a sort of chemist-cum-smallholder. He used to dispense his pills, and that sort of things, and I suppose she had a smattering of \'85 she wouldn't be a highly qualified person, 
not from the point of view of nursing, but she was quite a useful person.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember what the girls thought of the welfare worker? You know, the girls who used to \'85
? I wonder if sometimes, you know, the ones that your mother had as lodgers, whether they accepted this, or whether they were resentful of her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well actually, they didn't have a lot to do with her because, see, they were comfortable in our home and they had their own interests then. I mean they were interested in the Chapel and o
ne was sort of learning to play a violin, and so they didn't really want to use those facilities much, so apart from sort of being recommended to come to us, I don't think they had sort of much to do with the welfare services. And I don't recall any of th
em ever being ill, so, you know, they didn't require visits or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember in that period any trade union activity, any attempts at organization in the mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, a good while before that. I couldn't give you the exact year, but it was quite early on. The girls \'85
. But perhaps I better start first of all with the men. Now, there were a body of men who were called Overlookers. They were, like, the aristocrats of the work people down there. The
y were the people who attended to the looms and if there was anything wrong, they corrected them. In fact, they were really responsible in that sense for seeing the cloth was made correctly. And they'd put in comparatively new machinery for those days whi
c
h was being used in the North of England and they brought down some men from the North, from Lancashire and Yorkshire, who were acquainted with those looms, to start them up here. Well, you see, those men coming from the North, I mean, were already trade 
unionists, you see, and of course coming here \'85 and then \'85
. Actually, they wanted paying the same money as they had in Yorkshire, otherwise they wouldn't have come down, you see, which was considerably more than what was paid to overlookers here, you see. A
nd of course, they hadn't been here very long before they all got together, sort of thing, and the local men who were overlookers said 'we want paying the same as them for doing the same work'. And the management said, 'oh, no, we're not going to do that,
 you're paid what we agreed to pay you before', and so it went on like that, until they organised the union here for the men, you see. Of course, there was considerable opposition from the management.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What did they call that union then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It was th
e National Association of Power Loom Overlookers. And the manager of the company definitely said 'well, that's no good, we shan't .. we shall never pay the money', you know, 'we shall never pay you the same as them', and it was no good saying we do the sa
m
e work and our work is as good as theirs, they just said 'we don't think it is and we shan't pay you'. But eventually, of course, that went the way that those things do. Eventually they had to pay it and the men were recognised. And the girls then were ..
..
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember if there was actually a strike?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no strike, no, there were threats and all that sort of thing. There wasn't a strike.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Were you actually working there when that happened, or did you hear about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 That was just a 
little bit before I went, yes. Because actually, when I went down there - and later I was to become an apprentice overlooker, you see - and I was accepted in the trade union, you know, right from the commencement. So, you see, that was established, like, 
when I went in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 When did you become an overlooker, can you tell me roughly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well, I was apprenticed in the end of 1914, and that was for a 5 years' apprenticeship. But that was broken, you see, because I went off into the Forces, in the First World War.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Tell me about the girls now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well, the girls was something rather different, you see, and to an extent I think it was connected with the founding of a branch of the Independent Labour Party in Halstead. There were a little nucleus of you
 know, very fine people - in my opinion very fine people, I knew them - who got together in that little party of, you know, Independent Socialists, or Independent Labour Party they called it then, and strangely enough our head designer at Cou}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13648689\charrsid6246232 rtaulds was one of them, a man n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13648689\charrsid6246232 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
ed Brough. And then there was another one, a Baptists Minister's son, Percy Morley. And then there were a family of girls who, I think, 3 out of the 4 of them worked at Courtaulds, named Newton. The father worked at Courtaulds and lived
 in one of the company houses. Now, as I say, all these people belonged to the Independent Labour Party, and I think later Reg's father joined. And, you know, I think this idea of organising for trade unionism sort of, really, like, emanated from there an
d these girls being down at Courtaulds, you see, were able to continue the work, sort of \'85
 or at least, follow up this idea. And they really did, they did wonderful work there in getting these girls organised in face of opposition. You may have heard of Mary McArthur.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, I have.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well, she at that time was contemporary with us, and she came down here and you know, helped sort of, organise them. And they did form a branch of \'85 you know \'85 it wasn't the Workers' Union then, it was a textile union, b
ut I wouldn't be quite sure of the name. But anyway, they did form a union and, you know, they got supported nationally and people, as I say, like Mary McArthur, and that came down. And incidentally one of these girls eventually became Lady Shepherd, the 
Secretary of the National Labour Party. It was \'85 she wasn't Lady Shepherd then, I mean, she was the \'85
 Shepherd was the Secretary of the National Labour Party and she sort of married him and then, of course, eventually he was knighted, you know, by one of the Labour governments and he finished up \'85
 actually his son is the leader of the Labour opposition now, Shepherd. Not Labour opposition, the Government, in the House of Lords. That's her son, not that I think much of him, but still, that's beside the point.
 But, you know, they were outstanding girls and not only \'85 you see, they had the advantage to \'85
 as well as being intelligent, they were extremely goodlookers, you know. They were striking persons, you know, and you could say 'well, that doesn't help', but it does, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How many of them were there, do you think? How many of these girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
There were 4, but one of them worked in a shop and the other 3 all worked down at Courtaulds. Mind you, there were others as well, but they were the lights, 
and the prime, sort of, movers and they really got quite strong in the town, you know, I mean. That's one thing about this little town, you know. In that sense it had always been sort of progressive from the point of view of the liberal attitude to things
,
 you know. I mean it wasn't like a lot of these little towns in rural areas, you know, sort of all died-in-the-wool Tory and stay that way and, you know, 'thank you very much, Sir' at every move, I mean, there was always an indepence in Halstead that way,
 and they certainly did display it that way. You mention, like, was there a strike. I can't recall a strike, but I do recall just before I went there, there was some trouble and these girls threatened to \'85 I mean all the work people, you know \'85
 threatened to throw the manager in the river, because there's a nice river flows comfortably by the mill, you see. And, you know, they went round to his house and they were going to pull him out and throw him in the river. But there was no \'85
 that was a temporary stoppage, you know, there was no sort of prolonged strike, I think, not from what I gathered afterwards that \'85 you know, he was such a terrible }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13648689\charrsid6246232 character}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 , but things weren't quite right and I think at that time where was a lot of anti-German feeling in the coun
try and he happened to have been a German and, you know, therefore, that was all centred on him, like. I wasn't there, and they didn't put him in the river, but as you say, you know, he very nearly had it. And I think there was, you know, \'85
 they stopped work, but I don't think it was for any length of time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 But that union that you joined when you became an overlooker, that was the first union you joined, was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, that was the first union I joined, yes. And of course, they were a hundred per cent., you know, I mean they \'85
 there were no overlookers there that were not members of the union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I think you said that your father was a Liberal?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 That's right, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember taking part in any elections or doing any work in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Not in those days, no. To me that was just a bit of fun, you know, where people were plastering one another's doors and windows with blue or yellow and we used to wear ribbons and sing 'The Lord Gave the Land to The People', that was one of the bat
tle cries of the liberal, and that sort of thing. And the non-conformist parson's words were, you know, liberal to all man, you know, they used to speak about it in their sermons. The church, of course, were recognised, you know, as Conservatives, and tha
t was as clearly defined as that, you know. But, you know, to me elections, at that age, were as I say, just a bit of fun, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 When you first started work and got half a crown a week how much did you give to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, all of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You didn't keep any back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, no, no, no.! She had it all, and used to give me, sometimes a 6d.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What would you spend that on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 There'd be 2d. to go and watch the local football club play on a Saturday afternoon, and well, perhaps a sweet, 
or something. Later on, getting bold, packet of Woodbines, which we used to \'85
 we were not supposed to smoke, but we used to, you know, get a packet of Woodbines, which cost a penny, then and go out into the fields and make ourselves feel queer, you now, smoking them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 When you got your 3/6d. a week was it the same, you continued to hand it all to your Mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 How long did you continue doing that? Quite a time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, that went on until I was \'85 'till I joined up, I used to give it all to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What year did you join the Forces?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, I was coming up to 18.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 That would have been about 1917, would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, I joined about a couple of months before I should have been called up, and I did that because I wan
ted to get into the Flying Corps, you see. If you waited until you was called up then you went where they put you, you see, but by going in earlier you had some choice. So that's how, you know, how it come about.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 When you left in 1917, what pay were you getting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, now you've beaten me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 It doesn't matter. I wondered if you knew. What sort of work were you doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I suppose I'd be getting \'85 oh, twelve, 13 shillings a week. Well, I was an apprentice, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You'd started your apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 What year did you start that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I started that the end of 1914, yes, about 1914 - 15.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember how the decision was taken, or how it came about that you became apprenticed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, I \'85 you know, had good 
reports, because I had no influence. Usually, you know, there was, like, the plum jobs for boys and you had to get either someone, your father, or someone pulled a string, you know. But I had no one like that but, you know, I did get picked out and consid
ered meself very lucky. I suppose I was under those circumstances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Were there many more people wanting apprenticeships than were \'85?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, yes, yes. As I say that was, you know, looked upon as, like, for a working man, one of the plum jobs, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And all the time, up through this period were talking about, did you have the same hours, whatever kind of work you were doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did everyone at work have the same hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 With the exception of the office staff, who used to go to work at 8 o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember at that time feeling that employers and workers had different interests, that there was this conflict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, not \'85 no, no. No political or industrial sense at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you think you were a class conscious person? Do you think you were aware of your status as a working class person, at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I suppose I was to a degree. Yes, I suppose I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember being made to feel any middle class or richer people discriminating
 against you, or saying things against you in any way? Or children at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Well, in a way, like. Because even after, you know, I'd started work it was one of my jobs to take this washing home to the people who, you know \'85.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Sent it to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Sent it to Mother to do and occasionally some of, you know, my contemporaries, like, you know, would sort of make some remarks about, you know, the fact that I had to take the washing home and that sort of thing, and I was a bit sensitive, you k
now, and I used to sort of, you know, feel a little bit, sort of, you know, sorry about that, but not serious. As I say, I never wore a chip, you know, on my shoulder, but there were occasions, you know, like that where \'85
 I mean, some children, you know, c
an be sort of pretty beastly that way, you know, and specially those who, you know, apparently got all that they wanted, you know, and didn't have to worry about, you know, the things that sort of my mother was worrying about, and so I did feel it sometim
es, but that was about the only occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 
Do you remember your mother and father themselves, how they brought you up to see yourself in relation to other people either in a class way, or generally in behaviour? Sort of moral training they gave you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, my mother's attitude to that was, 'you're as good as anyone else'. That sums it up, sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You were brought up with their consciousness, were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, yes. She was, you know, sort of 'not having you second wicket'. That was
 her attitude and she'd jolly well say so, too. You know, very independent; self-reliant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 And your father, do you remember his having that kind of attitude?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no, he was docile.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Keep his place, more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, oh, yes, definitely. When y
ou said, like what activities did the church engage in and I said yes, we had the Band of Hope, and you said did I sign the pledge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Funny thing. My sister was \'85 we were talking the other day. She, like me was a member of the Son
s of Temperance, which was a friendly society, you see. I think it's still active today. But it was very strong here and she mentioned \'85
 I mean, she was very young, and the time came, like, when she had to be initiated and she had to sign the pledge, you s
ee. Well, she loved going to this meeting, whatever it was, with all her friends, and that sort of thing, and they'd all signed the pledge and then it came, like for her turn, you see, and they said 'now, we want you to sign this', and she said, 'well, I'
m
 not going to sign it'. And the secretary looked at her and he said, 'well, sign it, 'you know, 'cos one of her aunts had been a prominent figure in this Sons of Temperance Society. And she said, 'well, I won't sign it', and he said, 'well, then you can't
 join the movement'. And she said she went home, you know, thinking, you know, 'whatever will Mother say to me', she said, 'I just, you know, didn't think I \'85
 'not because she was interested in drink or anything like that, but just being told that she'd got
 to sign this pledge, you see. And she said to herself, whatever will Mother say to me, you know, now with Auntie Emma being such a big noise in this Society and me refusing to sign the pledge. She said she went home to Mother, you know, expecting to be s
o
rt of well and truly ticked off about it, like, and when she told Mother, like, she said, 'oh well. Well, Amy girl, I wouldn't do what they say'. And that was that. There was a touch of the old spirit, like, in her, you see, and so she didn't sign the ple
dge.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Does she take after your mother, do you think, in the way of independence?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, she did in a way. Oh, yes, definitely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Do you remember your parents bringing you up with any particular fear of the police? Or attitude towards the police and the law?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Your mother didn't say she'd call a policeman, or anything like that if you were naughty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, I don't think she ever used that expression, you know. If we were naughty, she'd deal with it herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did you have different clothes on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes. Oh, yes, yes, we always had a Sunday suit. Oh, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Were you supposed to be very careful of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes! \{illegible\}, I mean, that was something that had to be taken care of.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did you keep it on all through Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Oh, yes, you know, we kept it on all through Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 When you were working, how did your mother buy your clothes? Did she buy it out of what you gave her?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 I wondered if she set aside a certain amount. Do you know if she apportioned the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, it's as I said, you know, she had this Co-Op dividend, you see, that she \'85
 used to be the basis, you know, of the payment of those things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Can you remember any family outings that you did together as a family? Or excursions, when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Not much, other than that factory outing to Yarmouth. Oh, and sometimes a cheap excursion down to Clacton by train, which was \'85
 oh, I don't know, about a shilling return or something, then. You know, very cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 You remember doing that all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Yes, we did that, you know, together. And then this occasional trip to Bocking, or Braintree in that waggonette.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Did you ever go on any Co-Op outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 No, no. I don't think they had any. T
here used to be an annual treat that the Co-Op used to give here and we all used to, you know, sort of go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 But that was in Halstead?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 That was in Halstead, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14644286 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Where would that have been
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8984427 FW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990402\charrsid6246232 Well, that was held down Parsley Street. They had a large field there that they used for grazing, beside the river.
